Frontal or nasal neuromasts not present, one pre-orbital neuromast in short shallow open groove; post-orbital and supra-orbital neuromast system provided with large neuromasts and large lobes, covering a great part of the groove; pre-opercular neuromast system with 5 pores; lobes of supra-temporal neuromast system very prominent, even visible with the naked eye. A µCT scan of two specimens showed the following characters: total number of 30 vertebrae, hypurals fused to one hypural plate, ten caudal fin rays attached to hypural plate, posterior neural and hemal spines flattened, the top of the latter fused to hypural plate (
Fig. 8
). Scales cycloid, body completely scaled except ventral head surface, two to three rows of scales underneath the eye, frontal squamation of G-type, no scales on dorsal and anal fin base, scales on mid longitudinal series 21–23 . Number of dorsal fin rays 11–13 , anal fin rays 18–20 , caudal fin rays 24–27 , pelvic fin rays 6 , pectoral fin rays 11–13 . First dorsal fin ray above anal fin ray 8–10 .

Colouration. Live specimens. Males (
Fig. 6
). Back olive brown changing to orange below dorsal fin, flanks silverish with light green shine, changing to white on ventral side, snout and lower jaw orange. Flanks with four to five rows of scales anteriorly edged with black crescent shaped markings. Median fins and pelvic fins orange. Caudal fin with posterior white edge. Pectoral fins translucent. Narrow black band along base of anal fin. Urogenital papilla black.

Preserved in ethanol. Males (
Fig. 7
). Back brown, flanks light brown, ventrally edged with a band of black pigmentation, ventral side below this band whitish. Snout dark brown. Black pigmentation on flanks and anal fin as in live specimens. Pectoral fins translucent, all other fins greyish, caudal fin with posterior white edge.

Females (
Fig. 7
). As males, less black pigmentation on flanks, black band at base of anal fin hardly visible, urogenital opening round, edged with small black spots.
